    <td width="7" valign="top" rowspan="52">&nbsp;</td>
    <td height="79" valign="top" colspan="5"> 
      <div align="center"><font face="Californian FB" size="5" color="#550909"><br>
        Survey of Native American History</font></div>
    </td>
    <td width="33"></td>
    <td></td>
  </tr>
  <tr> 
    <td colspan="2" height="425" valign="top"><img src="/web/20070420004640im_/http://mason.gmu.edu/~dgomez2/Native%20Americans/The%20Maya/Maya%20Introduction%20Essay/verticalborder.jpg" width="113" height="419"></td>
    <td width="278" valign="top" rowspan="39"><font face="Californian FB" size="4" color="#550909"><b>Sacred 
      Places </b></font><font face="Maiandra GD" size="3"><br>
      <br>
      <span class="body">Pyramids had very specific religious functions. Their 
      design, a four-sided form with stairs on one side and a temple on the flat 
      top, were quite sturdy. Their form enabled them to withstand earthquakes. 
      Many pyramids were dedicated to specific deities. There were over 70 pyramids 
      with raised temples alone in the sacred precinct at Tenochtitlan, including 
      <i>Quezalcoatl</i>, <i>Tezcatlipoca</i>, <i>Xipe Totec</i>, <i>Huitzilopochtli</i>, 
      and <i>Tlaloc</i>.</span></font> 
      <p class="body">Many pyramids were not particularly high. Their upper facades 
        and roof-combs were beautifully decorated with figures carved from stone 
        or stuccos that depicted scenes of ceremonies or conquest.The structure 
        atop the pyramids atop the pyramid is called the roof-comb. Illustrations 
        of Aztec pyramids reveals that the decorations and iconography of the 
        various roof-combs had very specific meanings. For example, <i>Tlaloc&#146;s</i> 
        pyramid had a blue roof-comb and aquatic symbols. </p>
      <p class="body">The <i>Templo Mayor of Tenochtitlan</i> was a dual pyramid 
        with a double staircase that led to a single platform. There were two 
        shrines at the top dedicated to two separate and distinct cults.</p>
      <p class="body">The Aztec temples at <i>Teotihuacan</i> were believed to 
        be a temple to the sun and moon. The Pyramid of the Moon was mot likely 
        associated with a fertility or water cult. In contrast, the Pyramid at 
        Mont Alb&aacute;n is rich in imagery of sacrificial victims and may have 
        been dedicated to a cult of war.</p>
      <p class="body">Some Maya pyramids were associated with deity cults, though 
        generally the pyramids were sacred places for ancestor worship. Pyramids 
        were built over the tombs of kings and other elite nobles. Thought the 
        pyramids were constructed to have ancestral tombs, they became centers 
        of worship.</p>
      <p class="body">Some pyramids, such as E-VII-sub at <i>Uaxact&uacute;n</i> 
        or the Castillo (Temple of Kukulcan) at <i>Ch&iacute;chen Itz&aacute;</i>, 
        were constructed for specific celebrations, such as the completion of 
        periods of time. The Temple of the Warrior, also at <i>Ch&iacute;chen 
        Itz&aacute;</i>, was most probably dedicated to warfare and the cult of 
        the ruler.</p>
      <p class="body">Pyramids are similar in shape to mountains and may have 
        been built as sacred mountains. The double-pyramid at <i>Tenochtitlan</i> 
        was dedicated to <i>Huitzilopochtli </i>and <i>Tlaloc</i> and was a symbolic 
        recreation of <i>Coatepec</i>, the hill where <i>Huitzilopochtli</i> was 
        born.</p>
      <p class="body">The Aztec word for temple was <i>Teocalli</i> or &#147;God 
        House&#148; and was used to refer to a place of worship. Priests went 
        to these sacred spaces to make offerings, to request divine intervention, 
        or to commune with their gods. The Aztec sacred precinct consisted of 
        78 buildings. Most of the structures were temples devoted to a specific 
        deity or cult. Priestly schools and residences also were located in the 
        holy compound. </p>
      <p class="body">Some contemporary scholars have argued that not all monumental 
        Mesoamerican structures were necessarily temples or palaces. Until further 
        research can confirm their function archaeologists now prefer to assign 
        neutral numbers (for example, E-VII-sub) rather than a name, (for example, 
        Temple of the Giant Jaguar).<br>
      </p>
      <span class="body"><font face="Maiandra GD" size="3"></font></span></td>
